\pard\fs24\lang2057\f1\fs27\cf1\b\ltrpar\ql\sb450\sa45\li150\ri45 Q1.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li567\ri567 Hex Baron\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 Hex Baron is a two-player game in which players issue commands to control pieces on a grid of hexagonal tiles. The winner is the player who has the most victory points (VPs) at the end of the game.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 When it is a player\u8217?s turn they give a series of three commands. Once all three commands have been given the program attempts to execute each command, in the order they were given. If an illegal command is given then that command will not be executed, but other commands given by the player will still be executed if they are legal. To successfully execute a command some of the resources in a player\u8217?s supply might need to be used (lumber, fuel and spare pieces).\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 The five available commands are:\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~\f2\fs20\sb0 move\f1\fs22\sb240 , used to move a piece from one tile to another\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~\f2\fs20 upgrade\f1\fs22 , used to change a piece into another type of piece\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~\f2\fs20 spawn\f1\fs22 , used to create a new piece\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~\f2\fs20 saw\f1\fs22 , used to obtain lumber\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~\f2\fs20 dig\f1\fs22 , used to obtain fuel.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567\fi0 Each tile:\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~has an ID\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~has a type of terrain\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~has (x, y, z) coordinates\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~is either empty or contains a piece.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567\fi0 The different types of terrain are:\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~forest (represented by the # symbol)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~peat bog (represented by the ~ symbol)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~field (represented by a space).\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567\fi0 In the default game there is a grid size of 8, which means that there are 32 tiles in the grid. Each tile is stored in a list and the position (index) of the tile in the list is used to identify it. The coordinates of the tile are sometimes used by the program, for example, when calculating the distance between two tiles.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 Figure 1\b0  shows the coordinates and indices for each of the tiles in the default game. The first number in a tile is the x-coordinate, the second number is the z-coordinate, the third number is the y-coordinate and the final number is the tile\u8217?s index (where it is in the list of tiles), which is its ID.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li567\ri567 Figure 2\b0  shows an example tile.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\qc\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0 Figure 1\par
\qc\sb240\sa0{\pict\jpegblip\picw9600\pich6165\picwgoal9600\pichgoal6165\picscalex100\picscaley100
}\b0 \~\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\qc\sb240\sa0 Figure 2\par
\qc\sb240\sa0{\pict\jpegblip\picw6810\pich3630\picwgoal6810\pichgoal3630\picscalex100\picscaley100
}\b0 \~\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 When the program displays the grid, for each tile it will show the type of terrain and, if there is a piece in the tile, the type of piece.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 There are four different types of piece available in the game.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \~\par

